<h2 id="what-is-a-normal-bmi-for-men">What Is a Normal BMI for Men?</h2>
  <p>According to the World Health Organization, the standard healthy BMI range for adult men — as for women — is 18.5 to 24.9. A BMI in this range is associated with the lowest overall health risk for most adult men.</p>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>BMI Range</th><th>Health Risk</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><span class="dot" style="background:#3A7BBF"></span>Underweight</td><td>Below 18.5</td><td>Nutritional deficiency risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="dot" style="background:#2D6A4F"></span>Normal weight</td><td>18.5 – 24.9</td><td>Lowest risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="dot" style="background:#C17B2A"></span>Overweight</td><td>25.0 – 29.9</td><td>Moderate increased risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="dot" style="background:#B83232"></span>Obese</td><td>30.0 and above</td><td>High to very high risk</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout"><p><strong>For Asian men:</strong> Research suggests that men of East and South Asian descent face higher health risks at lower BMI values. Many health organisations recommend using a lower overweight threshold of BMI 23 for Asian men, rather than the standard 25.</p></div>


